more transformer-based approaches, and we have heard excellent talks

513
00:30:57.478 --> 00:31:01.318
in the plenary sessions in the last days

514
00:31:01.458 --> 00:31:04.798
about how transformer-based approaches, which is sort of

515
00:31:04.858 --> 00:31:06.998
the algorithmic backbone

516
00:31:08.398 --> 00:31:09.518
of generative AI,

517
00:31:10.538 --> 00:31:12.918
have been used for biomedical questions.

518
00:31:13.338 --> 00:31:16.918
So we started out using vision transformer-based approaches, and

519
00:31:17.638 --> 00:31:21.388
2024 and 2025 have really been the way of pathology

520
00:31:21.478 --> 00:31:22.518
foundation models,

521
00:31:23.418 --> 00:31:26.918
where you include also text information.

522
00:31:26.958 --> 00:31:30.778
So you have vision language models, and you can start using language

523
00:31:30.818 --> 00:31:34.318
to sort of get your classification as a text

524
00:31:34.398 --> 00:31:38.018
output and start to interact with your image data.

525
00:31:38.208 --> 00:31:41.898
And now everyone is looking at artificial intelligence

526
00:31:42.078 --> 00:31:42.447
agents,

527
00:31:43.478 --> 00:31:46.878
which could really be the next step forward, hence

528
00:31:47.318 --> 00:31:47.998
this talk.

529
00:31:49.458 --> 00:31:53.338
So we have seen this slide already in this great presentation

530
00:31:53.378 --> 00:31:55.968
by Dr. Bitterman. What is an AI agent?

531
00:31:56.258 --> 00:31:58.018
This is a rather broad definition.

532
00:31:58.898 --> 00:32:02.568
An AI agent shows or has some level of autonomy and

533
00:32:02.658 --> 00:32:06.538
goal-directed behavior. It encompasses

534
00:32:06.578 --> 00:32:10.338
planning and reasoning capabilities, and it has

535
00:32:10.438 --> 00:32:12.318
some type or some degree of

536
00:32:13.238 --> 00:32:16.778
potential to interact with the environment it is living in.

537
00:32:16.818 --> 00:32:20.008
It can access tools, access additional memory, and access

538
00:32:20.818 --> 00:32:22.958
additional knowledge databases.

539
00:32:23.778 --> 00:32:27.098
This definition, as you've heard before, is rather broad

540
00:32:28.498 --> 00:32:32.218
as autonomy and agency in and of itself is sort of a spectrum.

541
00:32:32.278 --> 00:32:35.078
And we have seen this, so I will quickly go over this.

542
00:32:36.138 --> 00:32:39.878
You can use an LLM with a tool which

543
00:32:40.038 --> 00:32:43.598
then becomes an agent, and you can sort of then,

544
00:32:44.138 --> 00:32:48.118
like using Legos, put together your agentic AI workflow.

545
00:32:48.478 --> 00:32:52.178
You can have it in an iterative loop to tackle a question,

546
00:32:52.558 --> 00:32:56.458
but you can also use multi-agent systems where you have specialized

547
00:32:56.538 --> 00:33:00.518
models that have certain tools, and this is really what we think

548
00:33:00.558 --> 00:33:04.358
we can use to sort of model the pathological

549
00:33:04.478 --> 00:33:05.918
value chain. And

550
00:33:06.978 --> 00:33:10.878
this is some very preliminary results on how we imagine

551
00:33:10.918 --> 00:33:14.818
such a system to work. So we have an orchestrating agent that is

552
00:33:14.838 --> 00:33:15.678
sort of steering

553
00:33:16.838 --> 00:33:20.718
the whole workflow. And then we start out with a diagnostic AI

554
00:33:20.838 --> 00:33:24.708
agent, and this is a pathology foundation model that

555
00:33:24.738 --> 00:33:28.088
has been fine-tuned on just sort of describing the

556
00:33:28.178 --> 00:33:30.838
microscopy of, for example, a whole slide image.

557
00:33:31.398 --> 00:33:31.478
We

558
00:33:32.798 --> 00:33:35.598
think that we don't need this agent to be particularly

559
00:33:37.518 --> 00:33:40.188
accurate in giving an immediate diagnosis.

560
00:33:40.538 --> 00:33:44.468
It should just give a very accurate microscopic description and then pass this

561
00:33:44.538 --> 00:33:45.628
on to an

562
00:33:46.458 --> 00:33:49.158
LLM-based text analysis which

563
00:33:49.418 --> 00:33:53.328
has all the textbook knowledge about a certain entity that

564
00:33:53.358 --> 00:33:56.608
you are looking at. And it will then compare the microscopic

565
00:33:56.658 --> 00:34:00.598
description with the textbook knowledge and say,

566
00:34:00.648 --> 00:34:01.898
"Okay, this is

567
00:34:02.798 --> 00:34:06.618
my initial diagnosis, and you have to do these couple of

568
00:34:06.678 --> 00:34:09.778
tests to confirm, to verify, or

569
00:34:09.879 --> 00:34:13.359
falsify that initial instinct."

570
00:34:13.778 --> 00:34:17.488
And this can then access or interact with other

571
00:34:17.578 --> 00:34:21.537
tools. For example, AI agents that are very good at looking at

572
00:34:21.618 --> 00:34:25.598
immunohistochemistry. We are currently working on an AI agent that is

573
00:34:26.238 --> 00:34:29.848
incorporating our already clinically established next-generation sequencing

574
00:34:29.938 --> 00:34:30.778
pipeline

575
00:34:31.618 --> 00:34:35.438
to get the results directly into this agentic

576
00:34:35.558 --> 00:34:38.899
AI workflow. And then we have a reporting agent that can

577
00:34:40.399 --> 00:34:44.339
output a standardized report and include this into the clinical information

578
00:34:44.419 --> 00:34:47.598
system, for example. So this is a very

579
00:34:47.658 --> 00:34:48.558
preliminary

580
00:34:50.158 --> 00:34:52.899
minimum viable product that we have designed.

581
00:34:52.938 --> 00:34:56.018
So you have a WSI input, whole slide input.

582
00:34:56.308 --> 00:34:59.318
In this case, this is a lung cancer specimen.

583
00:34:59.778 --> 00:35:00.878
And then this

584
00:35:02.478 --> 00:35:06.438
fine-tuned pathology foundation model will then just

585
00:35:06.637 --> 00:35:08.478
output a microscopic description.

586
00:35:08.558 --> 00:35:12.538
For example, it says here, "Microscopic observation of atypical

587
00:35:12.678 --> 00:35:16.338
cells, squamous cells with intercellular bridges and keratinization."

588
00:35:16.798 --> 00:35:19.558
And this is then passed on to an LLM that uses

589
00:35:20.198 --> 00:35:24.178
RAG to access textbook knowledge and comes up with

590
00:35:24.198 --> 00:35:27.758
the initial diagnosis of a squamous cell carcinoma, and it

591
00:35:27.818 --> 00:35:30.538
immediately recommends additional

592
00:35:31.518 --> 00:35:35.128
immunohistochemical analyses. And now this could either

593
00:35:35.178 --> 00:35:38.218
trigger a further lab test

594
00:35:38.878 --> 00:35:39.258
or

595
00:35:40.898 --> 00:35:44.698
start our IHC robots in the lab. In this case, we

596
00:35:44.738 --> 00:35:45.618
have already

597
00:35:47.558 --> 00:35:51.038
performed these

598
00:35:51.098 --> 00:35:54.878
analyses and stored them into a

599
00:35:54.938 --> 00:35:58.638
folder that the agent can access. So

600
00:35:58.718 --> 00:36:02.678
it shows p40 and TTF-1. These are the clinical markers that we

601
00:36:02.698 --> 00:36:03.798
would also use.

602
00:36:04.618 --> 00:36:08.438
And then the IHC-specific agent correctly identifies

603
00:36:08.838 --> 00:36:11.938
p40 to be positive and TTF-1 to be negative.

604
00:36:12.298 --> 00:36:16.178
And in an iterative autonomous improvement loop, this is then passed again back

605
00:36:16.238 --> 00:36:19.538
to the LLM, which then comes up with a final

606
00:36:19.618 --> 00:36:23.478
diagnosis when it reaches a certain level of certainty and marks

607
00:36:23.538 --> 00:36:27.338
this case as resolved. We have the reporting agent

608
00:36:27.598 --> 00:36:31.458
that can give a final report in a structured

609
00:36:31.518 --> 00:36:31.798
manner.

610
00:36:32.698 --> 00:36:36.618
And the cool thing about this system is that it's based on open-source

611
00:36:36.658 --> 00:36:40.458
models. You can actually run this on-premise if you don't want to

612
00:36:40.518 --> 00:36:44.348
upload your sensitive medical information to

613
00:36:44.618 --> 00:36:45.178
some cloud.

614
00:36:46.438 --> 00:36:50.018
This particular system has very low computing requirement, and it's

615
00:36:51.558 --> 00:36:54.618
a modular system that you can sort of

616
00:36:54.718 --> 00:36:58.398
add additional capabilities to, such

617
00:36:58.538 --> 00:37:02.458
as NGS agents, for example. We have also included a reasoning

618
00:37:02.578 --> 00:37:04.498
trace for quality management

619
00:37:05.318 --> 00:37:09.054
purposes.Where you can sort of get the reasoning of each

620
00:37:09.394 --> 00:37:13.094
of the single agents as well. So the current

621
00:37:13.104 --> 00:37:14.374
directions are

622
00:37:15.374 --> 00:37:19.314
that we think that this approach could be very useful

623
00:37:19.654 --> 00:37:21.514
for multimodality

624
00:37:22.733 --> 00:37:25.954
questions. And the good thing is that we have already published on

625
00:37:27.494 --> 00:37:31.274
multimodality, so we have quite some data sets where we have

626
00:37:31.294 --> 00:37:35.134
radiological information, other pathological informations

627
00:37:35.634 --> 00:37:39.254
that we are now trying to include into our agentic AI

628
00:37:39.294 --> 00:37:42.274
approaches. We also want to use this for

629
00:37:42.574 --> 00:37:46.194
prognostication of problems and also

630
00:37:46.334 --> 00:37:48.914
therapy stratification in the future.

631
00:37:50.434 --> 00:37:53.974
We also think that this particular approach could be really

632
00:37:54.054 --> 00:37:57.894
valuable for rare tumor entities where pathological diagnosis

633
00:37:57.934 --> 00:38:01.074
